<p class="paragraph-P1"><span class="text-T4">Approaching the Buddha, ascetic Tissametteiya asked:</span><span class="text-T4"/></p>

<p class="paragraph-P1"><span class="text-T6">“</span><span class="text-T9">Who here in the world is content? …who has no disturbances? …what thoughtful one, having known both ends, is not stuck in the middle? …who do they say is a great man? …who here has escaped the seamstress?”</span><span class="text-T12"> </span></p>

<p class="paragraph-P1"><span class="text-T4">The Buddha replied:</span><span class="text-T4"/></p>

<p class="paragraph-P1"><span class="text-T9">“Leading the spiritual life among sensual pleasures… rid of craving, …ever mindful; a mendicant who, after appraisal, is quenched: that’s who has no disturbances.</span><span class="text-T12"> </span><span class="text-T9">That thoughtful one, having known both ends, is not stuck in the middle. He is a great man, I declare, he has escaped the seamstress here.”</span></p>
<p class="paragraph-P2"> </p>
<p class="paragraph-P1"><span class="text-T24">Notes: * </span><span class="text-T25">“Contact, bhikkhus, is one end; the arising of contact is the second end; the cessation of contact is in the middle; and craving is the seamstress. For craving sews one to the production of this or that state of existence. It is in this way that a bhikkhu directly knows what should be directly known; fully understands what should be fully understood; and by doing so, in this very life he makes an end of suffering</span><span class="text-T24">” see</span><span class="text-T25">: AN6: 61 (7) sutta, p. 352. ** The Buddha and arhants are great men, because they have escaped the seamstress.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-P1"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn1" href="#body_ftn1">i</a></span> <span class="text-T25">The 14th Dalai Lama, Tenzin Gyatso, spiritual leader of Tibet. This is a quote from the book:</span><span class="text-T25"/></p>

<p class="paragraph-P1"><span class="text-T25"> ‘Approaching the Buddhist Path’.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn30" href="#body_ftn30">ii</a></span> <span class="text-T26">Introduction to Majjima Nikaya by Bhikkhu Bodhi, see: MN: p.12, this is one of the 9 major qualities of the Buddha.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-P1"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn31" href="#body_ftn31">iii</a></span> <span class="text-T24">See</span><span class="text-T25">: MN:</span> <span class="text-T25">Vatthūpama Sutta-</span> <span class="text-T25">the Simile of the Cloth.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn32" href="#body_ftn32">iv</a></span> <span class="text-T26">He held the view that “growth” should be accomplished in the six senses by experiencing whatever sense objects one has never experienced before without clinging to those that are already familiar. His view thus seems close to the contemporary attitude that intensity and variety of experience is the ultimate good and should be pursued without inhibitions or restrictions, see: MN: Notes: 740, p. 1133.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn33" href="#body_ftn33">v</a></span> <span class="text-T28">The Buddha as ascetic Siddhartha met the King Bimbisara when he was wandering in Magada on his search of noble truth, see; Section 3. </span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn34" href="#body_ftn34">vi</a></span> <span class="text-T26">Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta, </span><span class="text-T27">Jain leader</span> <span class="text-T26">was a one of the popular religious teachers during the Buddha’s time.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn35" href="#body_ftn35">vii</a></span><span class="text-T26"> Both horns of the dilemma devised by the Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta presupposed that the Buddha would give a one-sided answer. Now that a one-sided answer has been rejected, the dilemma becomes inapplicable </span><span class="text-T30">see</span><span class="text-T26">: MN: Notes: 612, p. 1121. </span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn36" href="#body_ftn36">viii</a></span> <span class="text-T26">The 10 views are: (1) “‘The world is eternal; this alone is true, anything else is wrong’: such is my view, householder.” (2) Another wanderer said: “‘The world is non-eternal; this alone is true, anything else is wrong’: such is my view, householder.” (3)–(4) Still another said: “‘The world is finite’ … ‘The world is infinite’ … (5)–(6) ‘The soul and the body are the same’ … ‘The soul is one thing, the body another’ … (7)–(10) ‘The Tathāgata exists after death’ … ‘The Tathāgata does not exist after death’ … ‘The Tathāgata both exists and does not exist after death’ … ‘The Tathāgata neither exists nor does not exist after death’; this alone is true, anything else is wrong, see: AN:10: 93.3 View sutta, p. 534.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn37" href="#body_ftn37">ix</a></span><span class="text-T26"> Pavāraṇā ceremony: at the end of the 3 months rain retreat ( vassāvāsa) which held annually, each bhikkhu/ bhikkhuni  in order of seniority invites the sangha to point out any misconduct on his/her part; accordingly the Buddha too invited his disciples. </span><span class="text-T30">See</span><span class="text-T26">: SN: Notes: 513, p.567.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn38" href="#body_ftn38">x</a></span> <span class="text-T26">This extract is from Introduction to Devat</span><span class="text-T27">ā</span><span class="text-T26">samyutta by Bhikkhu Bodhi; see: SN: 1 Devat</span><span class="text-T27">ā</span><span class="text-T26">samyutta, p. 45. </span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn39" href="#body_ftn39">xi</a></span> <span class="text-T27">For Buddhism the devas are not immortal gods exercising a creative role in the cosmic process. They are simply elevated beings, blissful and luminous, who had previously dwelt in the human world but had been reborn in the celestial planes as the fruit of their meritorious deeds. With rare exceptions they are just as much in bondage to delusion and desire as human beings, and they equally stand in need of guidance from the Enlightened One. </span><span class="text-T30">See</span><span class="text-T26">: SN: Introduction: 1. Devat</span><span class="text-T27">ā</span><span class="text-T26">samyutta, p.45</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn40" href="#body_ftn40">xii</a></span> <span class="text-T27">“Brahmā was the supreme deity of early Brahmanism, conceived as the creator of the universe and venerated by the brahmins with sacrifices and rituals. The Buddha reinterpreted the idea of brahmā and transformed the single, all-powerful deity of the brahmins into a class of exalted gods dwelling in the form realm (rūpadhātu) far above the sense sphere heavens. Their abode is referred to as “the brahmā world,” of which there are many, of varying dimensions and degrees of hegemony…like all sentient beings, the brahmās are impermanent, still tied to the round of rebirth, though sometimes they forget this and imagine themselves immortal.</span><span class="text-T25"> </span><span class="text-T27">. </span><span class="text-T30">See</span><span class="text-T26">: SN: Introduction: 6. Brahmasamyutta, p.45</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-P1"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn41" href="#body_ftn41">xiii</a></span> <span class="text-T25">The yakkhas are fierce spirits inhabiting remote areas such as forests, hills, and abandoned caves. They are depicted as of hideous mien and wrathful temperament, but when given offerings and shown respect they become benign and may protect people rather than harm them. Many of the shrines that dotted the North Indian countryside were built to honour the yakkhas and secure their favours. Though living in misery, they have the potential for awakening and can attain the paths and fruits of the spiritual life, </span><span class="text-T24">see</span><span class="text-T25">: Introduction:  SN: 10 Yakkasamyutta, p. 55.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn42" href="#body_ftn42">xiv</a></span><span class="text-T26">  Prince Āḷavaka became one of the foremost lay followers of the Buddha; see: AN1: XIV Foremost,p.44</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn43" href="#body_ftn43">xv</a></span><span class="text-T26"> </span><span class="text-T30">See:</span><span class="text-T26"> SN: Notes: 594, p.580.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn44" href="#body_ftn44">xvi</a></span><span class="text-T26"> Brahma Baka is from the Brahma world, see: SN: Notes: 386, p.551.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn45" href="#body_ftn45">xvii</a></span><span class="text-T26"> In the sutta pointed out when Bodhisattva in a former birth was named teacher Kappa and his teacher was Kesava now the Brahma Baka. See: SN:Notes:391, p.552.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-P1"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn46" href="#body_ftn46">xviii</a></span>  This encounter also mentioned in <span class="text-T25">MN: Brahmanimantanika Sutta.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn47" href="#body_ftn47">xix</a></span><span class="text-T26">  Arahant bhikkhuni Dhammadinnā was declared by the Buddha the foremost bhikkhunı̄ disciple in expounding the Dhamma, see: MN:Notes: 459, p. 1107.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn48" href="#body_ftn48">xx</a></span><span class="text-T26"> He was the husband of venerable Dhammadinnā in her lay life and supported her to become nun.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn49" href="#body_ftn49">xxi</a></span> <span class="text-T26">8(13) The story of Nun Kisagotahmi- Verse 114: Treasury of Truth: Dhammapada by Ven. Weragoda Sarada Thero.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn50" href="#body_ftn50">xxii</a></span><span class="text-T26"> The name “Angulimāla” is an epithet meaning “garland (mālā) of fingers (anguli).” He was the son of the brahmin Bhaggava, a chaplain to King Pasenadi of Kosala. His given name was Ahiṁsaka, meaning “harmless one.” He studied at Takkasilā, where he became his teacher’s favourite. His fellow students, jealous of him, told the teacher that Ahiṁsaka had committed adultery with his wife. The teacher, intent on bringing Ahiṁsaka to ruin, commanded him to bring him a thousand human right-hand fingers as an honorarium. Ahiṁsaka lived in the Jālinı̄ forest, attacking travellers, cutting off a finger of each, and wearing them as a garland around his neck, see: MN: Notes: 820, p. 1140.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn51" href="#body_ftn51">xxiii</a></span><span class="text-T26"> Mahā Kaccāna, Master of Doctrinal Exposition by Bhikkhu Bodhi: Wheel No: 405/406: PBS:1995.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn52" href="#body_ftn52">xxiv</a></span><span class="text-T26"> This power was discussed</span><span class="text-T28"> in </span><span class="text-T29">section 5,</span><span class="text-T28"> under </span><span class="text-T26">Six Unshared Super-Normal Knowledges.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn53" href="#body_ftn53">xxv</a></span><span class="text-T26"> Subha’s father the brahmin Todeyya, was reborn as a dog in his own house because of his extreme stinginess. The Buddha identified him to Subha by getting the dog to dig up some hidden treasure Subha’s father had buried before his death. This inspired Subha’s confidence in the Buddha and moved him to approach and inquire about the workings of kamma. </span><span class="text-T30">See:</span><span class="text-T26"> MN: Notes: 1223, p1174.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn54" href="#body_ftn54">xxvi</a></span><span class="text-T26"> This sutta is best known under the name of “The Kālāma Sutta”; it shows how the Buddha encouraged </span><span class="text-T27">free inquiry in order to assess the truth.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn55" href="#body_ftn55">xxvii</a></span> <span class="text-T26">Before he met the Buddha, he had lived as an ascetic, convinced he was an arahant until a benevolent deity disabused him of this notion. He hastened to visit the Buddha in Sāvatthī. Upon receiving the Buddha’s teaching, he immediately attained arahantship. He was killed by a cow shortly after his attainment. Though he did not receive formal ordination, he is still considered a bhikkhu. </span><span class="text-T30">See:</span><span class="text-T26"> AN:Notes: 99, p. 585.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn56" href="#body_ftn56">xxviii</a></span> <span class="text-T30">See</span><span class="text-T26">: Ud</span><span class="text-T27">ā</span><span class="text-T26">na: 1.10 B</span><span class="text-T27">ā</span><span class="text-T26">hiya sutta: translated by Bhikkhu </span><span class="text-T27">Ã</span><span class="text-T26">nandajoti.</span></p>

<p class="paragraph-Endnote"><span class="footnodeNumber"><a class="Endnote_20_Symbol" id="ftn57" href="#body_ftn57">xxix</a></span><span class="text-T26"> He was a student of Bāvari, after listening to the Buddha, became one of his arahant disciples: see: KN:SuttaNip</span><span class="text-T27">ā</span><span class="text-T26">tha: Parayanvagg: Vatthug</span><span class="text-T27">ā</span><span class="text-T26">t</span><span class="text-T27">ā</span><span class="text-T26">, Translated by Bhokkhu Sujato: w.w.w.suttacentrl.net.
